Key Concepts Explained:
Job :
    It is the top-level unit of work. 
    It holds one or more Steps and is uniquely identified by its name plus the JobParameters you launch it with.
Step:
    It is a single phase inside a Job. 
    It can be chunk-oriented (read → process → write in a loop) or a Tasklet (one-shot logic like deleting temp files or sending a notification).
JobParameters:
    They are key-value pairs passed at launch time (e.g. run.date=2024-01-15). 
    They identify a unique JobInstance.
JobInstance:
    It represents one logical run of a Job with specific parameters. 
    If a JobInstance fails and you re-launch with the same parameters, Spring Batch resumes it — it does not start over.
JobExecution:
    It is one actual attempt to run a JobInstance. 
    A single JobInstance can have multiple JobExecutions (first attempt failed, second attempt succeeded).
JobRepository:
    It is Spring Batch's persistence backbone. 
    It stores all Job and Step metadata — statuses, counts, timestamps — in a relational database. 
    This is what makes restart possible.
ItemReader:
    It reads one item at a time from a source. 
    It returns null when the data is exhausted, which signals the chunk loop to stop.
ItemProcessor:
    It receives one item, transforms or validates it, and returns the result. 
    Returning null tells Spring Batch to skip that item entirely.
ItemWriter:
    It receives the full accumulated chunk (a list) and writes it in a single transaction.
    Built-in writers exist for JDBC, JPA, flat files, XML, Kafka, and more.
ExecutionContext:
    It is a key-value map scoped to a JobExecution or StepExecution.
    It survives a crash and is restored on restart — for example, storing the last successfully processed file line number.
Listeners:
    They are hooks around the job/step/chunk lifecycle — JobExecutionListener, StepExecutionListener, ChunkListener, ItemReadListener, etc.
    Used for logging, alerting, or custom cleanup.
Skip Policy:
    It declares which exceptions are safe to skip and up to how many times.
    Perfect for tolerating a handful of bad records in a million-row file without failing the whole job.
Retry Policy:
    It handles transient failures — for example, retrying a DB write up to 3 times on a deadlock exception before giving up.

Chunk-Oriented Processing Flow (Text Format):
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│               CHUNK PROCESSING LOOP                 │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

  Step starts
       │
       ▼
  BEGIN TRANSACTION
       │
       ▼
  ItemReader.read()
       │
       ├── returns null? ──► STEP COMPLETE (no more data)
       │
       ▼
  ItemProcessor.process(item)
       │
       ├── returns null? ──► skip this item, read next
       │
       ▼
  Add processed item to chunk buffer
       │
       ├── chunk NOT full? ──► go back to ItemReader.read()
       │
       ▼ (chunk full, e.g. 100 items)
  ItemWriter.write(chunk)
       │
       ├── success? ──► COMMIT TRANSACTION
       │                      │
       │                      └──► begin next chunk (loop back)
       │
       └── failure? ──► ROLLBACK TRANSACTION
                              │
                              └──► apply Skip / Retry policy

Job Lifecycle States (Text Format):
  [JobLauncher.run()]
          │
          ▼
       STARTING
          │
          ▼
       STARTED  ──────────────────────► STOPPED
          │                              (manually stopped,
          │                               can be restarted)
          ├──────────────────────────► FAILED
          │                              │
          │                              └──► re-launch with same
          │                                   params = RESUMES here
          ▼
       COMPLETED
          │
          ▼
       ABANDONED  (terminal, no restart)


  JobInstance  = Job name + same JobParameters (logical identity)
  JobExecution = one actual attempt to run a JobInstance

Common Built-in Readers and Writers:
READERS                              WRITERS
────────────────────────────────     ────────────────────────────────
FlatFileItemReader  (CSV, TSV)       FlatFileItemWriter
JdbcCursorItemReader                 JdbcBatchItemWriter
JdbcPagingItemReader                 JpaItemWriter
JpaPagingItemReader                  MongoItemWriter
MongoItemReader                      KafkaItemWriter
KafkaItemReader                      CompositeItemWriter (fan-out)
MultiResourceItemReader              ClassifierCompositeItemWriter
StaxEventItemReader (XML)            StaxEventItemWriter
JsonItemReader                       JsonFileItemWriter
